  "slug": "vichyssoise",
  "title": "Vichyssoise",
  "subtitle": "Chilled leek and potato soup, smooth, cold, and finished with cream",
  "excerpt": null,
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Vichyssoise is generally attributed to Louis Diat, a French chef working at the Ritz-Carlton Hotel in New York City, who created the dish around 1917 based on a leek and potato soup his mother made in Vichy, France. The recipe appears in Diat's Cooking à la Ritz (1941).",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Vichyssoise must be chilled before serving, allow at least 3 hours in the fridge. It is an ideal make-ahead soup. The sieving step after blending is what gives it the pale, satiny finish; a blended-but-unsieved leek and potato soup is still good but is a different dish.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
